Chloe laughed lightly and shook her head as she drove down the back country road.<br>
<br>
“I can’t believe he bought it,” she said.<br>
<br>
“I must say, I’m impressed,” Lex said, turning his face toward Chloe as she drove to give her a half-smirk, half-smile.  “Although you’re lucky he didn’t catch your ‘tell’.”  Chloe scoffed.<br>
<br>
“*I’m* lucky?”  She shook her head again.  “*You’re* lucky he didn’t catch on to your poorly hidden innuendo.”  <br>
<br>
“Please,” Lex said sarcastically.  “How many sexual innuendos have you thrown at him over the years?”<br>
<br>
“I don’t think that’s any of your business,” she said indignantly.  Lex smiled.<br>
<br>
“Uh-huh. And how many has he caught?”<br>
<br>
“None,” Chloe admitted.  She paused for a second and then furrowed her brow.  “And what do you mean, ‘my tell’?”    <br>
<br>
“It’s something that ---”<br>
<br>
“I *know* what a *tell* is, Lex,” Chloe interrupted.  Lex grinned and leaned back in his chair.<br>
<br>
“But, do you know what *your* tell is?”  He asked.  Chloe rolled her eyes and made a grumbling sound with her mouth.  “What was that?”  Lex asked, pretending not to catch what she had said.<br>
<br>
“I was fidgeting with my hands,” she said a little louder.  <br>
<br>
“Forgive me for asking, but if you know what your ‘tell’ is, then why didn’t you make an effort to stop?”  Lex asked.  Chloe shrugged.<br>
<br>
“It’s not like anyone has ever noticed it besides you,” she answered.  “Well, and my dad – which is probably why it’s so much easier to get away with lying to him over the phone.”  Lex chuckled at her sidetracked logic.<br>
<br>
“Probably,” he agreed.  A mischievous grin tugged at the corners of Chloe’s mouth.<br>
<br>
“I know your ‘tell’,” she said teasingly, her grin turning into an almost evil smile when Lex turned his head to stare at her with a completely serious expression on his face.<br>
<br>
“I don’t have a ‘tell’.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, you do.”<br>
<br>
“No, I --- fine.  Please, Miss Sullivan,” he said, emphasizing her last name, “what do you think my ‘tell’ is?”<br>
<br>
“It’s hard to explain,” she said.<br>
<br>
“I would imagine it’s impossible to explain, seeing as how I don’t have one,” he said smugly.  Chloe laughed and Lex’s smile fell.<br>
<br>
“It’s a combination,” Chloe said.  “First you do this semi-smirk thing, and then you use a certain tone of voice.”<br>
<br>
“Tone of voice?”<br>
<br>
“I’m sure it makes most people think you’re sincere,” Chloe said with a somewhat apologetic smile, but only so she wouldn’t risk getting him angrier with her.  <br>
<br>
“But not you.”<br>
<br>
“But not me,” she agreed.  “Tell you what, why don’t you turn on the radio so this doesn’t turn into a big argument over nothing?”<br>
<br>
“Avoidance,” Lex said in an admiring tone.  He smiled at Chloe.  “Well played, Sullivan.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you,” she said with a beaming smile.<br>
<br>
“Do I get to choose the music?”  He asked with a slight gleam in his eye.  Chloe looked at him apprehensively.<br>
<br>
“I – guess – so,” she strung out.  <br>
<br>
Lex smirked at her and turned on the radio.  He flipped through the different stations until he found an older song that he was familiar with, but he doubted Chloe knew.  Granted, it wouldn’t have been his usual taste in music, but it was hardly a usual situation he was in at the time either.  The music wafted out of the speakers and seemed to flow into the wind around them.<br>
